subtopics.content:
• HSBC India Services PMI rose to 60.5 in July from 60.4 in June – the highest level since August 2024. :contentReference[oaicite:0]{index=0}
• Growth driven by strong export orders and domestic sales, especially from finance and insurance sectors. :contentReference[oaicite:1]{index=1}
• Despite expansion, hiring slowed to a 15-month low, and price pressures rose, with input costs exceeding material gains. :contentReference[oaicite:2]{index=2}
• Composite PMI (services + manufacturing) climbed to 61.1 — fastest pace since April 2024. :contentReference[oaicite:3]{index=3}

• Service sector growth (PMI 60.5) bolstered by export orders, digital marketing, insurance & finance demand. :contentReference[oaicite:13]{index=13}
• Composite PMI at 61.1 — strongest since April 2024. :contentReference[oaicite:14]{index=14}
• Hiring slowed; inflationary pressures rise — likely considerations for RBI’s policy decisions ahead. :contentReference[oaicite:15]{index=15}

• Retail CPI inflation is expected to fall to an eight-year low of 1.76% in July. :contentReference[oaicite:2]{index=2}
• Core inflation (excluding food and fuel) eased to 4.20%, aiding disinflationary trend. :contentReference[oaicite:3]{index=3}
• Analysts expect further rate cuts in 2025 due to weak domestic demand and prolonged disinflation. :contentReference[oaicite:4]{index=4}

• Gross GST collections for July reached ₹1.96 lakh crore, up 7.5% YoY. :contentReference[oaicite:5]{index=5}
• Despite strong gross receipts, net revenue growth was marginal due to a 66.8% surge in refunds. :contentReference[oaicite:6]{index=6}
• Andhra Pradesh posted a record ₹3,803 cr gross GST in July, a 14% increase YoY. :contentReference[oaicite:7]{index=7}

• Merchandise trade deficit narrowed to $18.78 bn in June, down from $21.88 bn in May. :contentReference[oaicite:8]{index=8}
• In Q1 (Apr–June), cumulative deficit was $67.26 bn, up from $62.10 bn YoY. :contentReference[oaicite:9]{index=9}
• However, July’s trade gap widened again, estimated at $20.7 bn. :contentReference[oaicite:10]{index=10}
• Services exports grew 17%, remittances up 14% CAGR over 4 years, partially offsetting merchandise trade pressure. :contentReference[oaicite:11]{index=11}

• Net inflows into equity mutual funds surged 81% MoM in July, reaching ₹42,702 crore. :contentReference[oaicite:12]{index=12}
• SIP inflows hit a record ₹28,464 crore, with 91.1 million active SIP accounts. :contentReference[oaicite:13]{index=13}
• Total AUM crossed ₹75.36 lakh crore; small-cap funds saw a 61% jump, mid-cap +38%. :contentReference[oaicite:14]{index=14}

• HSBC Flash India Manufacturing PMI climbed to 59.2 in July, the highest in nearly 17½ years, fueled by robust domestic and global demand. :contentReference[oaicite:0]{index=0}
• S&P Global data confirmed a sharp uptick in new orders and production activity. :contentReference[oaicite:1]{index=1}
• Despite strong activity, business confidence flagged due to cost pressures and competition. :contentReference[oaicite:2]{index=2}

• Reuters economists’ poll projected CPI inflation at a record low of 1.76%, the lowest in 8 years, driven by subdued food prices. :contentReference[oaicite:5]{index=5}
• Forecasts from Mint and others estimated inflation between 1.1–1.8%, likely the lowest since 2014. :contentReference[oaicite:6]{index=6}
• Core CPI was estimated to ease to 4.20%, offering RBI flexibility. :contentReference[oaicite:7]{index=7}

• Equity (including hybrid) mutual fund net inflows jumped 81% MoM to ₹42,702 crore in July. :contentReference[oaicite:8]{index=8}
• Record SIP contribution of ₹28,464 crore and AUM crossed ₹75.36 lakh crore. :contentReference[oaicite:9]{index=9}
• Small- and mid-cap fund inflows surged 61% and 38%, respectively; large-cap funds rose 25%. Gold and silver ETFs also attracted ₹1,256 crore and ₹19,040 crore, respectively. :contentReference[oaicite:10]{index=10}

• Total mutual fund AUM rose to ₹75.36 lakh crore, up from ₹74.40 lakh crore in June. :contentReference[oaicite:11]{index=11}
• SIP book value reached ₹15.19 lakh crore with 91.1 million active SIP accounts. :contentReference[oaicite:12]{index=12}
• Retail investors accounted for roughly 27% of AUM, with HNIs holding about 34%, comprising over 61% of total assets. :contentReference[oaicite:13]{index=13}
